## Why cursor-based pagination is superior here

| Problem with `OFFSET` | How cursors fix it |
|---|---|
| **Expensive late pages** — `OFFSET 10000` forces PostgreSQL to read and discard 10,000 rows even if only 20 are needed. An index scan with a `WHERE` clause jumps straight to the right row. | The `WHERE (created_at < $1 OR …)` clause lands on the B-tree index directly; cost is O(limit) regardless of how deep into the feed you are. |
| **Drift under concurrent writes** — inserting a row on page 1 while the client reads page 2 pushes everything forward by one, causing rows to be duplicated or silently skipped across pages. | The cursor anchors to a specific `(created_at, id)` coordinate. New inserts don't affect rows already past that point. |
| **Expensive total count** — `SELECT COUNT(*)` on a large filtered table requires a full sequential or index scan on every request. | Eliminated entirely. `hasMore` is derived for free from the N+1 trick. |
| **Tie-breaking ambiguity** — sorting only by `created_at` means rows with identical timestamps have non-deterministic order, breaking pagination. | The compound `(created_at, id)` cursor is unambiguous because `id` is unique — even if a thousand posts share the same timestamp, the cursor always points to exactly one row. |

### Client usage pattern

```
GET /api/posts?limit=20                        # first page
GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=<nextCursor>     # second page
GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=<nextCursor>     # third page
# stop when pagination.hasMore === false
```

The cursor is intentionally opaque (`base64url`-encoded JSON) — clients must treat it as a black box and never construct or modify it, which frees you to change the internal encoding later without a breaking API change.

